---
description: Surface OpenBox governance state (active env, agent binding, behavior rules in scope) to every Cursor chat so the assistant respects guardrails before suggesting actions.
alwaysApply: true
---

openbox-governance:

- This workspace is governed by OpenBox. Every shell execution,
  file write, file delete, and MCP tool call passes through pre-
  action gates (`beforeShellExecution`, `beforeReadFile`,
  `beforeMCPExecution`, `preToolUse`) and post-action observation
  before completing.
- Treat any action that would touch a credential, run a destructive
  shell command (`rm -rf`, `sudo`, `curl | sh`), or hit a customer-
  facing endpoint as one that may be vetoed or require human
  approval. Do not assume your suggested commands will run.
- Before proposing destructive or external actions, check the
  current binding and gates with `/openbox-status`. If the user is
  already on a governed agent, prefer dry-running risky changes
  through `/openbox-check` before executing.
- If a hook returns `require_approval`, surface the pending row to
  the user via `/openbox-pending` so they can decide instead of
  retrying the action.
- Never propose disabling the OpenBox extension, removing
  `~/.cursor/hooks.json`, unsetting `openbox.agentId`, or running
  `openbox uninstall` to "make the warning go away" - the gates
  exist by policy. Suggest contacting the owner of the active
  policy instead.
- When the user asks "why did this fail / get blocked?", read the
  hook activity log via the **OpenBox Hooks** output channel in
  Cursor (registered by the extension) before guessing.
- For new agent integrations, default to spec-driven SDK usage
  (`openbox --experimental agent create`, `openbox --experimental behavior create`,
  `openbox --experimental guardrail create`); hand-coded HTTP calls bypass the
  governance shape and decay.
